\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, 42 U.S.C. \'a7 2000e, et seq., as amended ("Title VII") was intended to eradicate employment discrimination based \b \i0 \ul0 [*9]\b0 \i0 \ul0   on sex, including pregnancy.  42 U.S.C. \'a7 2000e(k).  Congress' actions were based, in large part, on a recognition that unemployment and occupational segregation have serious consequences for women and families, especially children.  As a result, Congress intended to strike at the "full range" of such practices.  (Point I)
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The facts upon which Congress relied remain true today.  Specifically, Congress recognized that women's employment is critical to the welfare of families (Point IA) that serious health consequences are associated with denial of employment opportunities (Point IB), and that stereotypes about women limit those opportunities.  (Point IC) Congress concluded that it was essential to make the right to work compatible with the right to have a family.  (Point ID)
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Congress thus expressed the commitment to full employment rights in unequivocal language.  (Point IIA).  The limited exception to the statutory mandate does not apply here.  In particular, costs of employing women or improving working conditions do not justify a policy that excludes women from employment opportunities.  (Point IIB) The lower courts that have attempted to craft new approaches \b \i0 \ul0 [*10]\b0 \i0 \ul0   to the statute's requirement have impermissibly distorted the statutory scheme.  (Point IIC) Enforcement of Title VII will return occupational health and safety determinations to federal regulatory authorities, whose efforts to improve workplace conditions have been undermined by the opinion of the court below.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 ARGUMENT
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Introduction
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This case presents the question of whether Title VII prohibits an employment practice that restricts opportunities for women who are willing and able to work because of the chance that they may become pregnant and that a workplace hazard may harm the fetus.  Judge Easterbrook, dissenting in the court below, considered it "likely the most important sex discrimination case in any court since . . . Congress enacted Title VII" and predicted that the decision, unless reversed, could limit women's access to as many as "20 million industrial jobs." International Union, UAW v. Johnson Controls, Appendix to the Petition For Certiorari (hereinafter "Pet. App.") at 99a and 100a.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This is no exaggeration.  In a variety of forms, these policies are already pervasive; they are most pronounced in industries historically closed to women, where high wages and \b \i0 \ul0 [*11]\b0 \i0 \ul0   good benefits make jobs particularly attractive to unskilled workers with few other options. n3 For many women and men, such employment offers the only alternative to poverty. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n3 See, Paul, et al., Corporate Response to Reproductive Hazards in the Workplace: Results of the Family, Work and Health Survey, 16 Am. J. Occ. Med. 267 (1989) reporting a higher incidence of discriminatory policies in male intensive industries.  See generally, Committee on Education and Labor, A Report on the EEOC, Title VII and Workplace Fetal Protection Policies in the 1980s, 101st Cong., 2d Sess. (Comm. Print 1990) (hereinafter "House Committee Report").
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The court of appeals' characterization that women take these jobs "to better the family's station in life," Pet. App. at 51a, understates the significance of this kind of employment to the well-being of women and their families.  The stories of women and men affected by these discriminatory policies offer an insight into the reality of life outside the courtroom walls and graphically illustrate the profound personal and economic effects of policies requiring women to choose between their jobs and their fertility.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Most of these women are deeply \b \i0 \ul0 [*12]\b0 \i0 \ul0   concerned about the health and well-being of their families.  These are not women who "might somehow rationally discount" the risks of work and selfishly sacrifice the health of their children for mere "financial reward." Pet. App. at 51a and 21a.  They work because they must, at the best jobs they can get.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 [When] I began working in the foundry of an automobile plant . . . I had one small child and when my husband and I separated, I needed to find a job with good salary and benefits.  The plant was the only place in the area that offered both . . .  If I lost my job I would never find anything comparable to what I now have.  A woman who is in her late thirties as I am would probably only be able to get a job as a sales clerk in the shopping mall or as a waitress in a fast food restaurant.  (A-71-72) n4 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n4 References are to Appendix pages at which individual Statements of Interest are set forth.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * * *
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 [After] I quit school in the 10th grade . . . I worked for five years as a sales clerk . . . [at] minimum wage. . . .  [When] I heard that they were hiring women at [the] plant I applied for the job because it offered a much better salary and better benefits . . .  \b \i0 \ul0 [*13]\b0 \i0 \ul0   A-65-66
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * * *
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I am the major supporter of my family.  My husband is presently laid off from his job.  My family depends on my salary and benefits, and it would be disastrous for us if I lost my job before my husband is called back to work.  A-74
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Their counterparts are men who are plagued by concerns about the effects of workplace hazards on themselves and their future children.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1978 or 1979 [my brother] was tested and had a very high blood lead level.  In 1980 or 1981 he collapsed on the job melting ore (iron) in the melting area . . .  [He] was forty four years old when he had the heart attack, and . . . I strongly believe [it] may very well have been caused by the many years he spent working in the high lead melting area and nearby areas.  A-46
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * * *
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I have worked in the automotive industry for twenty-five years . . .  Only three of my five children are alive . . .  I am convinced that my exposure to hazardous substances in the workplace was the cause of the two deaths and possibly the premature birth of [my] twins . . .  A-63
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Both men and women have little information and fewer choices.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 You might say that we're sort of caught between a rock and a hard \b \i0 \ul0 [*14]\b0 \i0 \ul0   place.  Some men prefer to ignore the health issue and just gamble that they or their children won't get sick.  A-65
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * * *
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I decided to have the sterilization because I needed to keep my job . . .  I knew that my husband and I were going to separate, and that I would have to support myself and my son.  In addition, I had always helped my parents who were elderly and infirm . . .  I was 26 years old when I was sterilized.  A-52-53
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Johnson Controls has elected to disregard the risks of lead to male workers and to "protect" women by denying them jobs instead of improving workplace conditions. n5 In validating this approach, the decision below is inconsistent with the conclusions of federal health authorities that men and women require an equivalent degree of workplace protection to safeguard their own health and that of future generations.  It also conflicts with regulations adopted pursuant to the Occupational Safety and Health Act, 29 U.S.C. \'a7 651, et seq. ("OSH Act") that require employers to protect both men and women planning families at the level of exposure at which Johnson Controls excludes women. n6 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n5 Johnson Controls' assertion that hazardous conditions cannot be improved is palpably untrue, as federal regulators and public health experts have found.  See Brief amici curiae of the American Public Health Ass'n, et al.  ("APHA Brief").  If Johnson Controls could not comply with occupational health standards, it would be required to apply to the Secretary of Labor for a variance.  29 U.S.C. \'a7 655(6)(A).  See also General Electric Co. v. Secretary of Labor, 576 F.2d 558 (3d Cir. 1978).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n6 Final Standard for Occupational Exposure to Lead, 29 C.F.R. \'a7 1910.1025 (1989).  OSHA's Lead Standard and subsequent regulatory actions regarding lead are discussed extensively in the APHA Brief.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*15]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The lower court assumed that women will make inappropriate decisions about work and childbearing; it would defer to "an employer [who] adopts an employment policy designed to address a difficult societal problem," Pet. App. at 49a, even though that policy offers neither workplace safety for men nor equity for women.  The court thus ignored not only the Congressional mandate expressed in OSHA, but also the conclusions Congress reached in enacting and amending Title VII, that unemployment and underemployment pose serious risks for women and their families, and that women cannot be forced to forego childbearing in order to work.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I.  The Objectives Congress Sought To Achieve When It Adopted And Amended Title VII Are Directly Threatened By Policies Such As Johnson Controls'
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Title VII prohibits intentional sex discrimination in employment unless sex is a bona fide occupational qualification ("BFOQ").  42 U.S.C. \'a7 2000e-2(e)(1).  Phillips v. Martin Marietta Corp., 400 U.S. 542 (1971). Cf. Price Waterhouse v. Hopkins, U.S.  , 109 S.Ct. 1775 (1989) (mixed motive case).  In response to Gilbert v. General Electric, 429 U.S. 677 (1976), \b \i0 \ul0 [*16]\b0 \i0 \ul0   holding that pregnancy-based discrimination was not per se gender-based discrimination within the meaning of Title VII, Congress enacted the Pregnancy Discrimination Act ("PDA") "to make plain that, under Title VII . . . discrimination based on pregnancy, childbirth and related medical conditions is discrimination based on sex.  Thus, the bill defines sex discrimination, as proscribed in the existing statute, to include these physiological occurrences peculiar to women[.]" n7 The PDA further "illustrate[s] how discrimination against pregnancy is to be remedied." n8 Women, whether or not pregnant, are entitled to employment opportunities based solely on the "ability or inability to work." 42 U.S.C. \'a7 2000e(k). 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n7 Comm. on Labor and Human Resources, Legislative History of the Pregnancy Discrimination Act of 1978, 96th Cong., 2d Sess. 40-41 (Comm. Print. 1979) (hereinafter "Legis. Hist.") (emphasis supplied).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n8 California Federal Savings and Loan Association v. Guerra, 479 U.S. 272, 285 (1987). (hereinafter "Cal Fed")
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Because women are as capable of producing batteries as men are, the plain language of Title VII, as amended by the PDA,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*17]\b0 \i0 \ul0   clearly prohibits Johnson Controls' policy, regardless of whether that policy is construed as discriminating against all women or potentially pregnant women. n9 As the extensive legislative record underlying the PDA reveals, Title VII was intended to redress "the full range of discriminatory practices which have adversely affected [women's] status in the work force." n10 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n9 The court below concluded that the policy did not apply to all women, but affected only those capable of bearing children.  E.g., Pet. App. at 43a.  The terms of the policy, however, draw explicit gender based lines.  All women (but no men), for example are required to submit medical evidence of sterility as a condition of employment.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n10 Legis. Hist., supra note 7 at 63.  (emphasis supplied).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In particular, Congress recognized that women's employment is critical to the welfare of women and families, that denial of access to employment opportunities results in a lower standard of living with devastating consequences, and that sex-based stereotypes limit women's employment opportunities.  In consideration of both the equity of women's claim to equal employment opportunity and the practical necessity of \b \i0 \ul0 [*18]\b0 \i0 \ul0   work for many women, Congress expressly endorsed the proposition that no woman should have to sacrifice the right to work in order to have a family, nor sacrifice the right to have a family in order to work.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 As demonstrated below, policies like Johnson Controls' directly threaten the principal goals to be achieved by Title VII's prohibitions on sex discrimination.  A construction of the statute permitting such policies would frustrate its very purposes.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A.  Women's Employment Is Critical To The Welfare Of The Family.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Policies that deny women employment reflect an assumption that women can forego employment without serious consequences, but the facts are otherwise.  In both single parent and dual wage earner households, women's employment is critical to the maintenance of many families, and the loss or reduction of a woman's income will have devastating effects, as Congress acknowledged:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In many low-income families the financial support provided by the mother has become essential for the families' economic survival. . . .  In an increasing number of middle-income families the support and the well being of the family has become inextricably tied to the income generated by females.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*19]\b0 \i0 \ul0   n11 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n11 Legis. Hist., supra note 7 at 127.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In dual wage earner families, fulltime working wives contribute an average of 37.6% of the family income, and the poorer the family, the more critical the wife's contribution.  In families in which the total income is less than $ 15,000, that contribution averages more than half. n12 In 1984, for example, poverty was 35% lower than it would have been had wives not worked. n13 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n12 Supporting A Family: Providing the Basics: Hearing Before the House Comm. on Children, Youth, and Families, 98th Cong. 1st Sess., 39-40 (1983) (Statement of Diana Pearce) (hereinafter "Supporting A Family").  Among black couples, the median family income of those families with a wife in the paid labor force was nearly double that of families where the wife did not go out to work, and among Hispanics, it was nearly 75% higher.  Appendix, "Median Annual Income of Families by Family Type, Race and Hispanic Origin, 1987," in The American Woman 1990-91, A Status Report 362 (S. Rix, ed. 1990).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n13 Work in America: Implications for Families: Hearing Before the House Select Comm. on Children, Youth, And Families, 99th Cong., 2d Sess. 4 (1986) (Opening Statement of George Miller) (hereinafter "Work in America").
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*20]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A significant number of women are primary or sole wage earners.  Approximately 45% of women in the labor force are single, separated, divorced or widowed. n14 Many of these women have families and many are poor. n15 Another 15% of women in the labor force are married to men earning less than $ 15,000 a year. n16 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n14 Women's Bureau, Office of the Secretary, U.S. Dept. of Labor, Fact Sheet No. 88-2, Facts on Women Workers, P9 (1988) (hereinafter "Facts on Women Workers").
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n15 Nearly half of all female headed households (including both working and non-working mothers) were in poverty in 1987, and most of these were households with children.  U.S. Children and Their Families: Current Conditions and Recent Trends, 1989, H.R. Rep. No. 356, 101st Cong., 1st Sess. 110-11 (1989) (hereinafter "Children and their Families").  Female headed households represent an increasing share of all families in poverty (51.4% in 1986 as compared to 45.7% in 1982).  Children and Families in Poverty: The Struggle to Survive: Hearing Before the House Select Comm. on Children, Youth, and Families, 100th Cong., 2d Sess. 11 (1988).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n16 Facts on Women Workers, supra note 14 at P19.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In recognition of \b \i0 \ul0 [*21]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the fact that women were in the workforce because of "pressing economic need" and required "protection for their financial security and the security of their families", n17 Congress was particularly concerned about practices that restricted women's access to lucrative and desirable employment and froze them in the status of marginal workers.  Statistics on the extent of wage disparity due to occupational segregation reflect the pervasiveness of such practices and Congress found them "shocking". n18 The data reveal that the problem is particularly acute for unskilled women who are concentrated in low-paying, female intensive industries n19 and minimum wage jobs. n20 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n17 Legis. Hist., supra note 7 at 61.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n18 Id.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n19 There is a clear inverse correlation between wages and the proportion of female employees in jobs.  Work in America, supra note 13 at 29, Table 4 (Statement of Janet Norwood).  In 1981, the expected median wage in occupations filled exclusively by women was less than half that of the median in exclusively male occupations.  National Academy of Sciences, National Research Council, Women's Work, Men's Work, Sex Segregation on the Job (B. Reskin, H. Hartmann, eds.) 1, 10 (1986).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n20 Smith, "The Paradox of Women's Poverty: Wage Earning Women and Economic Transformation," Women and Poverty 122, 137 (C. Gelpi, et al., eds., 1986).  Minimum wage now equals only about three-quarters of federal poverty guidelines for a family of three.  Children's Defense Fund, "The Unmaking of Decent Family Income" in A Vision for America's Future 18 (1989) (hereinafter "Vision for America's Future").
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*22]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Access to non-traditional jobs is therefore especially important to unskilled women if they are to escape from poverty and attain economic security for themselves and their families.  Title VII and other civil rights measures brought these women the promise of such employment, n21 but policies like Johnson Controls' would close the workplace doors once again.  Indeed, sex-based policies take their most extreme and oppressive form in occupations characterized by high wages, good benefits, and entrenched gender-based segregation. n22 Johnson Controls' policy, effectively excluding women from all employment in its battery plants, is typical of restrictions in male dominated industries. n23 Thus, women are now subject to exclusion from the very jobs and occupations that Congress specifically identified as critical to their economic well being and that of their families. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n21 See, e.g., Becker, From Muller v. Oregon to Fetal Vulnerability Policies, 53 U. Chi. L. Rev. 1219, 1239 (1986).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n22 Id.  See note 3, supra.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n23 For example, the policy adopted by the Olin Corporation in 1978 excluded fertile women from five of eleven lines of progression in one division and some jobs elsewhere.  Wright v. Olin, 697 F.2d 1172, 1182 (4th Cir. 1982). General Motors' "fetal protection" policy "virtually forecloses the employment of women altogether" at its battery plants.  Scott, "Keeping Women in Their Place," in Double Exposure 180, 181 (Chavkin, ed. 1984).  And see Grant v. General Motors, appeal filed (6th Cir. No. 89-3478).  Rules barring fertile women from various jobs have reportedly been adopted by Monsanto, B. F. Goodrich, Union Carbide, American Cyanamid, St. Joe's Minerals Bunker Hill Smelter, Gulf Oil and others.  Becker, supra note 21 at 1226-27; House Committee Report, supra note 3 at 6.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*23]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Gender-based policies are less extreme and less common in other occupations, but occur there too, with the effect of denying women employment security and continuity of wages. n24 These examples reveal that if a woman's employment can be limited because she could become pregnant and her employer perceives some risk, the reach of such policies is virtually unlimited. n25 Judge Easterbrook commented:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A female bus or taxi driver is exposed to noxious fumes and the risks of accidents, all hazardous to a child she carries.  Would it follow that taxi and bus companies can refuse to hire women?  That an employer could forbid pregnant employees to drive cars because of the risks accidents pose to fetuses?  For all we can tell, Johnson's argument compels us to answer "yes" to these questions. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n24 For example, both Hayes v. Shelby Memorial Hospital, 726 F.2d 1543 (11th Cir. 1984) and Zuniga v. Kleberg County Hospital, 692 F.2d 986 (5th Cir. 1982) involved x-ray technicians who were fired when they became pregnant even though both were well within universally accepted safety limits for pregnant women.  AT&T has barred pregnant women from jobs at computer chip processing plants because of unconfirmed reports of reproductive health hazards.  Bureau of National Affairs.  Pregnancy and Employment: The Complete Handbook on Discrimination, Maternity Leave and Health and Safety 66 (1987).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n25 Employers do, in fact, exclude women from work based on their own assessment of risk and in the face of medical opinion to the contrary.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 [When] my supervisor learned that I was pregnant, she told me I would have to stop working. . . .  [E]ven with my doctor's authorization, I was laid off. . . .  These last six months have been hard for us. . . .  [W]e cannot make ends meet every month.  A-68-69.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * * *
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 [W]hen the personnel director learned that I was pregnant, I was told that I couldn't stay on the job.  I wasn't given any reason, and even my doctor said that I could continue working.  The personnel director informed me that if I had wanted to keep my job then I shouldn't have gotten pregnant. . . .  I was told that the only way I could get my job back would be to lose the baby.  I was very upset.  No one was able to help.  The union was unable to do anything and my doctor refused to sign the papers for disability because he said I could still work.  A few days [after this] I miscarried the pregnancy.  A-40-41.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*24]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Pet. App. at 92a.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Congressional disapproval of all these results - denial of employment, mandatory pregnancy leave, or other limitations - could not be clearer:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In some of these cases, the employer refused to consider women for particular types of jobs on the grounds that they might become pregnant. . . .  A common practice has been to place women on mandatory unpaid leave, regardless of their ability or inability to work.  In some cases, women discriminated against are permitted to return to their former employment after delivery; but in other cases mandatory leave results in loss of previous position, lower pay and loss of employment security.  In the extreme case, women who have become pregnant are simply terminated by their employers. n26 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n26 Legis. Hist., supra note 7 at 61-62.  See A-48, A-68, and A-58.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 B.  By Assuring Equal Employment Opportunities, Congress Intended To Improve The Health And Well Being Of Women And Their Families.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Testimony before Congress during the hearings on the PDA documented the link between all types of discriminatory employment practices and the health and well being of women and their families.  Congress recognized that when women are \b \i0 \ul0 [*25]\b0 \i0 \ul0   denied access to good jobs and adequate benefits, their families -- especially the children n27 -- suffer the consequences. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n27 The risk, of course, extends to adults as well.  Unemployed workers who are unable to provide for their families face heightened risk of disease poverty, and malnutrition.  Physician Task Force on Hunger in America, "Malnutrition, Ill-Health, and Hunger" in Hunger in America (1985) at 128-29 (hereinafter "Hunger in America" See, Estimating the Effects of Economic Change on National Health and Social Well-Being, S. Doc. No. 198, 98th Cong. 2d Sess. (1984).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The loss of a mother's salary will have a serious effect on the family unit, making it difficult for parents to provide their children with proper nutrition and health care.  For some women and their families, it will mean dissipating family savings and security, or being forced to go on welfare. n28 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n28 Legis. Hist., supra note 7 at 3 (statement of Senator Williams).  This is no hyperbole:
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 When I began earning more money [at the factory] I took out a personal loan to help me get ahead on some of my other bills.  I was not rehired [after a layoff and because of pregnancy].  The factory also discontinued my insurance coverage. . . .  Since March of 1989, I have had no income, no insurance and am currently receiving AFDC.  A-60.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*26]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Income is inversely related to nutritional deficiency in children, n29 and both are linked with a host of negative health effects including delayed growth, weakened resistance to infection and increased vulnerability to environmental toxins. n30 Ironically, children from poor families are at particular risk of lead exposure, and black children face the greatest risk. n31 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n29 Hunger in America, supra note 27 at 115.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n30 Id. at 99, 116, 118-122; Ebuonu and Starfield, Child Health and Social Status, 69 Pediatrics 550 (1982).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n31 In 1980, the proportion of children with blood leads in excess of 30 ug/dl in families with annual incomes less than $ 6,000 was nearly ten times greater than the proportion in families with incomes in excess of $ 15,000.  For children in families with incomes from $ 6,000 to $ 15,000, the proportion was nearly four to one.  Lead from paint in deteriorating housing and high air lead levels in inner cities are the primary sources of childhood exposure.  Controlling for all other variables, it was found that black children have higher blood lead levels than white children.  Mahaffey, et al., National Estimates of Blood Lead Levels: United States, 1976-1980, 307 New Eng. J. of Med. 573, 577 (1982).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*27]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In general, there is a higher frequency of health problems among poor children.  Poor children receive less medical care than wealthier children; they are more likely to suffer from medical illnesses and more likely to experience adverse consequences from illness. n32 The developmental hazards associated with poverty and malnutrition may be exacerbated by school absences or other health-related curtailments of normal childhood activities. n33 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n32 Starfield, Family Income, Ill Health, and Medical Care of U.S. Children, 3 J. of Public Health Policy 245, 247 (1982).  At every age level and for every cause of death, poor children die at a higher rate than non-poor.  Department of Human Services, State of Maine, Children's Deaths in Maine, 1976-1980 (Final Report) (1983).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n33 Hunger In America, supra note 27 at 101.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Full access to employment opportunities is also significant to the health of women and their families because critical benefits such as medical insurance are most commonly available in larger firms n34 and in unionized, male dominated occupations. n35 It is not surprising, therefore, that among women of childbearing age, those most likely to be uninsured \b \i0 \ul0 [*28]\b0 \i0 \ul0   are either unemployed or working in low wage jobs. n36 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n34 See, Pepper Commission Documentation of Findings, Prepared for Bipartisan Commission on Comprehensive Health Care 7 (Nov. 13, 1989, unpublished).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n35 Kamerman and Kahn, "Employers' Response to Their Employees" in The Responsive Workplace: Employers and a Changing Labor Force 60-61 (1987).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n36 Adolescent Pregnancy Prevention: Prenatal Care Campaign, Children's Defense Fund, The Health of America's Children: Maternal and Child Health Data Book 48 (1989) (hereinafter "Health of America's Children").  Black women are more likely to be uninsured than their white counterparts.  Id.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Lack of adequate insurance has specific negative health consequences. n37 The uninsured are more likely to delay seeking medical care. n38 Many uninsured children are treated only in response to an immediate crisis and seldom receive essential preventative pediatric services. n39 This is also true in insured, but low income families, since many policies require significant employee contributions, n40 have high deductibles and/or exclude the cost of preventative care. n41 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n37 See Supporting A Family, supra note 12 at 54.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n38 Gold, et al., Health Insurance Loss Among the Unemployed: Extent of the Problem and Policy Options, 8 J. of Public Health Policy 44, 54 (1987).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n39 Supporting A Family, supra note 12 at 57.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n40 Family income is correlated not only with presence of insurance coverage, but also with the extent of employer contribution.  Only 27.3% of the children in poor but working households were covered by a plan fully subsidized by the employer in 1986.  Health of America's Children, supra note 36 at 45.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n41 See, A Vision For America's Children, supra note 20 at 9.  The uninsured and inadequately insured can, and do incur substantial out-of-pocket health care expenses, sometimes exceeding 20% of family income.  Supporting A Family, supra note 12 at 56.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*29]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Pregnant women's income and insurance benefits bear directly on the likelihood of good pregnancy and birth outcomes.  Congress specifically acknowledged the "concrete connection between loss of income during pregnancy and a deterioration of the health of the pregnant woman and her child which results from impaired access to a healthful life situation." n42 Lack of prenatal care and inadequate maternal nutrition, both of which are correlated with poverty, n43 are also strongly associated with low birth weight and prematurity, the causes of most infant morbidity and mortality in the United States. n44 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n42 Legis. Hist., supra note 7 at 65.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n43 It has been demonstrated repeatedly that financial constraints are the most significant obstacle to attaining adequate prenatal care, Health of America's Children, supra note 36 at 52, and poverty is, of course, linked with nutritional deficiencies.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n44 See, Binsacca, et al., Factors Associated with Low Birth Weight in an Inner City Population: The Role of Financial Problems, 77 Am. J. Pub. Health 505 (1987).  See also, Children and Families, supra note 15 at 179.  It has been found, for example, that babies born to mothers who received no care were:
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 (1) over six times more likely to be born prematurely;
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 (2) over three times more likely to be low birthweight;
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 (3) four times as likely to measure low Apgar scores at birth; and
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 (4) two-and-a-half times more likely to require intensive care.  See Moore, et al., " The Perinatal and Economic impact of Prenatal care in a low socioeconomic population" (1985) (unpublished manuscript).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Some of these outcomes have been specifically linked to inadequate maternal nutrition.  See, e.g. Hunger in America, supra note 27 at 117.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*30]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The cost effectiveness of prenatal health care has been well documented, n45 and this fact was repeatedly emphasized in testimony presented to Congress by the American Nurses Association in support of the PDA. n46 The evidence was a critical element in Congress' assessment of the overall costs associated with employment discrimination against women.  Responding to employers' arguments that the PDA would increase the costs of employing women, Senator Williams, one of the sponsors of the legislation, stated:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 We must also consider the cost which is imposed on society when working women and their families are denied adequate income for a decent standard of living.  This cost is felt in terms of medical complications for both the women and their children ... n47 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n45 See, e.g. Children and Families supra note 15 at 39 ("early, comprehensive prenatal care. . . saves over $ 3 for each $ 1 invested.") Regular pediatric care is also cost effective.  See, A Vision For America's Future, supra note 20 at 12 (Children receiving such care have annual health care costs 10% lower than children not receiving such care).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n46 Discrimination on the Basis of Pregnancy, 1977: Hearings on S.995 Before the Subcomm. on Labor of the Senate Comm. on Human Resources, 95th Cong., 1st Sess. 466 (1977) (Statement of American Nurses' Association).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n47 Legis. Hist., supra note 7 at 65-66.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*31]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Congress perceived that the threat to women, their children and other dependents was substantial, and that the price tag of discrimination was high.  It concluded that full access to employment was the necessary and appropriate response.  Johnson Controls would have the Court reevaluate the Congressional equation and find it invalid.  But striking this balance is a matter of social policy, therefore a job for Congress, not the courts.  Moreover, the conclusion reached by Congress twenty-five years ago, and reaffirmed twelve years ago, remains valid.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 C.  Congress Sought To Eliminate Stereotypes That Limited Women's Employment Opportunities.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Johnson Controls' policy assumes that all women who are capable of becoming pregnant will do so, indeed that they might be pregnant at any moment.  The policy applies to all women, regardless of their circumstances, their desire to become pregnant, or the likelihood of pregnancy. n48 Even though most women do become pregnant at some time in their lives, it is the grossest form of stereotyping to assume that every woman who is capable of conceiving is always about to do so.  Once again, the policy at issue in this case threatens a principal \b \i0 \ul0 [*32]\b0 \i0 \ul0   purpose of Title VII: to eliminate decision-making based on group characteristics, especially when the result is to deny job opportunities to individuals capable of working.  The Court has cautioned that:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Even a true generalization about the class is an insufficient reason for disqualifying an individual to whom the generalization does not apply. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n48 As noted above, the company's policy, is similar to many others in its total disregard for the individual factors relating to the likelihood of pregnancy.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 At this time [when the policy excluding fertile women was introduced] I was married and had no plans to have any children.  I thought that I would be exempt from the policy because my husband had a vasectomy.  However, the plant manager told me that even though my husband had been sterilized, I could still "screw around".  A-37-38.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 See also A-51-52.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  Los Angeles Dep't. of Water and Power v. Manhart, 435 U.S. 702, 708 (1978).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Here, in fact, the generalization is not only impermissible, it is also not true.  The probability of bearing a child depends on a number of factors including marital status, n49 sexual orientation, family situation, age, number of existing \b \i0 \ul0 [*33]\b0 \i0 \ul0   children, birth control method n50 and attitude toward abortion.  Women's role in the workforce are also significant to their reproductive choices.  The fertility rate in the United States in the last decades has declined steadily, n51 a trend that is both a cause and an effect of women's increased participation in the labor force. n52 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n49 Johnson Controls' policy applies to women of all ages.  Pet. App. at 72a-73a.  (Posner, J. dissenting).  However, the birth rate is near zero at age 40, with only a 0.39 percent probability that a woman between the ages of 40 and 44 will give birth and a 0.02 percent probability that a woman age 45 to 49 will give birth in a given year.  U.S. Department of Commerce, Bureau of the Census, Statistical Abstract of the United States (1987) at 59 (1984 rates).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n50 The risk of unintended pregnancy among fertile, sexually active women is only 6.5%.  Public Health Service, U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, No. 182, Advance Data, Contraceptive Use in the United States, 1973-88 (March 20, 1990).  Only slightly more than half of the unintended pregnancies (53%) will result in a live birth.  R. Gold, Abortion and Women's Health, A Turning Point For America (1990) at 11.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n51 See Children and Their Families, supra n.15 at 9.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n52 P. Roos, Gender and Work: A Comparative Analysis of Industrial Societies, (1985) at 15, 121-22.  In the last ten years, women have accounted for more than three-fifths (62%) of the increase in the civilian labor force.  Facts on Women Workers, supra note 14 at P1.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*34]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 During the duration of the company's voluntary program (1979-1983), in which women were allegedly counselled about workplace risks associated with pregnancy, n53 there were only 8 pregnancies among approximately 275 female workers. n54 The numbers suggest that the risk of harm to future children of Johnson Controls female employees is very small indeed.  Moreover, given the small number of women involved, it is difficult to understand why the company made no effort to treat women on an individualized basis. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n53 The explanation and release signed by each female employee read as follows:
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Lead's effect on the adult person is well understood and we keep people safe and healthy. . .  But when it comes to the effect of lead on an unborn child, we know a lot less. .  .but we do know enough to be able to tell you that there are some risks. . .of [a spontaneous] abortion. . .[T]he evidence [of any such risk] is not as clear, for example, as the relationship between cigarette smoking and cancer. . . there is some evidence that animals fed or exposed to airborne lead run the risk of having congenitally affected offspring. . . .
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Affidavit of Jean Beaudoin, (August 12, 1986) Exhibit J (Globe Union Policy Guidelines for Women in Lead Exposure) (emphasis supplied).  Women were not guaranteed transfers to comparable jobs during pregnancy.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n54 Id. Exhibit K (Selected Pregnancy Data For Plants Under Voluntary Fetal Protection Program).  Affidavit of Eunice Williams dated Nov. 27, 1984, P4 (establishing number of women employees).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*35]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Nevertheless, Johnson Controls seeks to bar all women because a few will become pregnant.  Its policy is based solely on class characteristics that do not necessarily apply to individuals and are not job-related.  This is precisely the type of decision-making that is an anathema to Title VII.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 D.  Congress Intended To Enable Women To Combine Employment And Family Life.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Congress was aware that the PDA would preclude employers from adopting policies that restricted women's employment to protect the fetus, but declined to carve out a special exception based on such concerns. n55 Moreover, the Senate was particularly troubled by the possibility that restrictive employment policies based on pregnancy might force women to have unwanted abortions in order to keep their jobs. n56 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n55 The Chamber of Commerce opposed the legislation, in part because the PDA would prohibit employment decisions based on concerns for the health of a pregnant woman or her child.  The issue was raised in the hearings in a question to Andre Hellegers, M.D. who testified that men and fetuses all require equivalent protection.  See APHA Brief, pp. 10-12.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n56 See, e.g., Legis. Hist., supra note 7 at 116 ("One of our basic purposes in introducing this bill is to prevent the tragedy of an unwanted abortion forced on a woman because she cannot afford to leave her job without pay to carry out the full term of her pregnancy").  Congress also addressed the possibility that employers might attempt to impose their own ethical values on employees and retaliate against women who had abortions.  See e.g., id. at 117.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*36]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 As a result of these concerns, Congress repeatedly emphasized that Title VII was intended to enable women to combine work and family life and to permit them to make personal decisions without employment related consequences.  The language varies, but the message is clear and consistent.  Congress sought to offer women "protection and security without fear of reprisal due to their decision to bear children" n57 and to "put an end to an unrealistic and unfair system that forces women to chose between family and career[.]" n58 Indeed, the "entire thrust" of the PDA was "to guarantee women the basic right to participate fully and equally in the workforce without denying them the fundamental right to full participation in family life." n59 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n57 124 Cong. Rec. 21440 (1978) (Remarks of Rep. Chisholm).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n58 124 Cong. Rec. 21442 (1978) (Remarks of Rep. Tsongas).  This is precisely the problem presented by the type of policy adopted by Johnson Controls.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 . . . Generally I'd say that I felt less a woman because of the operation.  I think that though my marriage was in bad shape, my sterilization made things even worse.  . . .[It has] even affected my second marriage.  Both my second husband and I would have very much liked to have had a child together.  In fact I tried to have the operation reversed, but was not successful.  A-53.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n59 123 Cong. Rec. 29658 (1977) (Remarks of Senator Williams).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*37]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The policy at issue in this case, which conditions full employment rights on women's willingness to relinquish their fertility directly contravenes the legislative intent.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * * *
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In sum, Congress clearly considered the economic, social and personal costs incurred when women are denied good jobs and employment security.  It weighed the benefits of full employment against the costs of opening jobs to women and struck the balance in favor of full and equal employment opportunities.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 II.  The Plain Language Of Title VII Clearly Reflects Congress' Objectives To Prohibit Policies Like Johnson Controls.'
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A.  The Statutory Mandate is Unambiguous and Must Be Enforced.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Congress' decision to provide women full and equal employment rights, including the right to make their own choices about working, was expressed in the clearest of statutory mandates.  Title VII prohibits employment discrimination on the basis of sex, including "pregnancy, childbirth or related medical conditions".  Further, it requires that women, including those affected by pregnancy childbirth or related medical conditions be treated the same "for all employment related purposes. . . as others not so affected but \b \i0 \ul0 [*38]\b0 \i0 \ul0   similar in their ability or inability to work." 42 U.S.C. \'a7 2000e(k). n60 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n60 The Act's sole affirmative defense, BFOQ, permits exceptions based only on occupational qualifications, i.e., qualifications associated with job performance, and this is consistent with the clear intent and plain language of the PDA.  This Court has not addressed the meaning of the BFOQ defense in a sex discrimination case brought after the adoption of the PDA, but prior interpretations are consistent with the understanding that the defense must be closely linked to performance of important job functions.  See Dothard v. Rawlinson, 433 U.S. 321 (1977) and Western Air Lines v. Criswell, 472 U.S. 400 (1982).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The PDA restated Congress' original intent to prohibit all forms of sex discrimination. n61 This Court recognized this Congressional purpose recently, in California Federal Savings and Loan Association v. Guerra, 479 U.S. 272 (1987). Despite divergent views on the applicability of the Act in other contexts, eight members of the Court agreed that the PDA prohibits intentional discrimination against women who are or might be pregnant,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*39]\b0 \i0 \ul0   but who are able to work. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n61 Prior to enactment of Title VII, rules barring marriage and motherhood for female employees were commonplace.  E.g., Phillips v. Martin Marietta Corp., 400 U.S. 542 (1971) (per curiam). Pregnant women were placed on mandatory maternity leave, Cleveland Board of Education v. LaFleur, 414 U.S. 632 (1974), and were denied accrued seniority and other benefits.  Cf.  Nashville Gas Co. v. Satty, 434 U.S. 136 (1977). Pregnancy was widely excluded from employment-related health insurance and disability plans.  Gilbert v. General Electric Co., 429 U.S. 125 (1976), Geduldig v. Aiello, 417 U.S. 484 (1974). The legislative history of the PDA reveals Congressional intent to solve the problem of sex and pregnancy discrimination definitively.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The majority opinion acknowledged the controlling significance of the "ability or inability to work" language of the statute: the "second clause was intended to . . . illustrate how discrimination against pregnancy is to be remedied." Cal Fed, 479 U.S. at 285. This reading was necessary to effectuate the Congressional purpose "to provide relief \b \i0 \ul0 [*40]\b0 \i0 \ul0   for working women," id. at 286, and to "'protect [them] from the full range of discriminatory practices.'" Id. at 299 n.3 (White, J., dissenting).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Justice White, writing for himself, Justice Powell and Chief Justice Rehnquist, disagreed with the majority's conclusion that the statute permits state mandated preferential treatment of pregnant workers, n62 but had no disagreement regarding its absolute prohibition on the type of discriminatory practice involved here.  Quoting from the Senate Report that "'treatment of pregnant women. . .must focus. . .on the actual effects of their condition on their ability to work'," Justice White noted that the "'ability to work'" language means "'exactly what it says in a situation where it is directly implicated.'" Id. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n62 Unlike Cal Fed, there is no suggestion here that the policy at issue might help "'to achieve equality of employment opportunities and remove barriers.'" Id. at 288, quoting Griggs v. Duke Power Co., 401 U.S. 424, 429-30 (1971).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The opinions of the members of the Court sitting in the Cal Fed case evidence virtually unanimous recognition of the PDA's purpose to eradicate \b \i0 \ul0 [*41]\b0 \i0 \ul0   all forms of discrimination against women based on sex or childbearing capacity. n63 As the Court acknowledged, the commitment to provide women full employment rights was conditioned only on the "ability to work" standard. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n63 Justices Stevens and Scalia, concurring, addressed other issues not relevant here, but indicated no disagreement with these principles as articulated in the majority opinion.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This result is not surprising.  Numerous decisions of this Court have reiterated that "the starting point for interpreting a statute is the language of the statute itself.  Absent a clearly expressed legislative intention to the contrary, the language must ordinarily be regarded as conclusive." Consumers Product Safety Commission v. GTE Sylvania, 447 U.S. 102, 108 (1980). The duty of the federal courts to enforce the plain language of federal statutes precludes independent judicial assessment of the wisdom of Congress' decision:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Our individual appraisal of the wisdom or unwisdom of a particular course selected by Congress is to be put aside in the process of interpreting a statute.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  TVA v. Hill, 437 U.S . 153, 194-95 (1978).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Even if this Court, like \b \i0 \ul0 [*42]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the majority of the Seventh Circuit, were to disagree with Congress' conclusion that employers may not substitute their evaluation of the risks and benefits of work (including the risks and benefits to current and future children) for the decisions of women themselves, it is bound by the Congressional decision to the contrary, precisely because certain judgments are committed to the legislative process:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 [The Court has] no expert knowledge on the subject, much less do we have a mandate from the people to strike a balance of equities. . . Congress has spoken in the plainest of words, making it abundantly clear that the balance has been struck.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  Id. at 194.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 B.  The Possibility That Employer Costs Will Increase As A Result of Women's Employment Does Not Affect the Statutory Mandate Against Discrimination.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Departures from the statutory mandate are not permitted even if additional costs may result from compliance:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Even a very high cost could not justify continuation of the policy of discrimination against pregnant women which has played such a major part in the pattern of sex discrimination in this country. n64 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n64 Legis. Hist, supra note 7 at 48.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 As a result,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*43]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the Court has invalidated the use of accurate, sex-based actuarial tables in setting pension and life insurance rates, notwithstanding the fact that use of non-discriminatory tables would arguably increase employer costs.  Los Angeles Dep't of Water and Power v. Manhart, 435 U.S. 702. See also Arizona Governing Committee v. Norris, 463 U.S. 1073, 1084-65 n. 14 (1983) ("the greater costs of providing retirement benefits for female employees does not justify the use of a sex-based plan.") Thus, even if women did require additional protections from occupational exposures, Title VII would require that employers bear the costs of making the workplace safe. n65 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n65 Congress has sought to minimize the risks of employment for both working women and men through the Occupational Safety and Health Act, 29 U.S.C. \'a7 651, et seq., which requires that health protection be afforded at the "most protective" level, subject to constraints imposed by technological and economic feasibility.  American Textile Manufacturers Institute v. Donovan, 452 U.S. 490 (1981). It is entirely appropriate that the cost issue be addressed by a regulatory agency and on an industry-wide basis.  See APHA Brief.  A Title VII defense based on firm-specific "clean-up costs" would reward the least efficient employers by allowing them to discriminate while putting more viable concerns at a competitive disadvantage.  Such a defense could also result in irrational and inconsistent application of the statute, even within a single jurisdiction.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*44]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Johnson Controls did not assert a cost-based defense to this Title VII action, presumably in recognition of the Court's unambiguous holdings on the issue.  Nevertheless, the issue is addressed in the opinions in the court below.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The costs of providing equal employment opportunities in the face of recognized reproductive hazards might include not only the cost of making the workplace safe, but also the cost of potential tort liability to children of workers exposed to lead. n66 Judge Posner, in dissent, was particularly concerned with the second issue and suggested that such liability might at some point "become large enough to affect the company's normal mode of operation and supply the ground for a bona fide occupational qualification." Pet. App at 68a.  As noted above, this approach lacks statutory or precedential authority and indeed simply ignores the PDA's command that women who are able to work must be permitted to do so. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n66 In addition, both Judge Posner and the majority expressed some concern about the costs to society for caring for children who might be harmed by women's occupational exposure.  Indeed, despite the lack of any documentation, the majority relied on these potential costs to support its conclusion that the policy was jusitifed.  Pet. App. at 51a.  This approach is legally insupportable and totally inconsistent with Congress' conclusion that the social cost of denying women equal employment outweighed countervailing concerns.  The majority balanced the interests of "the employer, the employee, and the unborn child," Pet. App. at 42a, as if this were not a legislative function, and more importantly, as if the balance had not already been struck by Congress on the basis of careful consideration and extensive evidence.  See Point I, supra.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*45]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 There are, however, additional reasons to reject the suggestion that the potential for tort liability should constitute a defense in Title VII cases:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In today's litigious society, the potential for litigation rests in almost every human activity. . . .  The employer is, of course, free to protect itself from financially ruinous lawsuits by purchasing insurance and maintaining the degree of care required by law.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  Hayes v. Shelby Mem. Hosp., 726 F.2d at 1553 n.15. For a responsible employer, the risk of liability to children of female workers is remote, as discussed below.  In any event, there is also a risk of liability to children of male workers, as well as to consumers and others. n67 Johnson Controls and other employers with similar policies undertake these risks as a part of doing business.  They have presented no reason to suggest that any liability-related concerns associated with women's employment cannot be handled in precisely the same manner. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n67 Becker, supra note 21 at 1236-37, 1245.  (noting instances in which the children of male workers assert paternally-mediated genetic injury).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Johnson Controls can cite no suits brought by children of women workers exposed to lead.  On the other hand, there has been a tort suit brought by male workers, their wives and children alleging intentional injury or gross negligence.  Wade v. Johnson Controls, 693 F.2d 19 (2d Cir. 1982). There has also been at least one significant judgment against the company on the basis of defective products.  Jones, et al. v. Sears and Roebuck, Inc., Globe Union, Inc., et. al., No. 585-427 (Cal. Super. Ct., San Diego County, May 17, 1987), appeal filed No. D009904 (Cal. Ct. App., 4th App. Dist., Div. 1, filed Apr. 10, 1990) ($ 9.7 million jury verdict for plaintiffs injured by exploding battery).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*46]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Finally, permitting a defense based on potential liability would undermine the deterrence and safety-enhancing goals of tort law.  An employer who complies with OSHA standards, implements available technology to reduce exposures and adequately warns employees of remaining but unavoidable risks is not likely to be held liable to subsequently born children on either a negligence or strict liability theory.  n68 A cost-based defense would therefore eliminate any incentive created by the tort system to make the workplace safe, while giving employers wholesale license to exclude any class of workers they deem, for whatever reason, particularly vulnerable. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n68 See generally, 1 S. Pegalis and H. Wachsman, American Law of Medical Malpractice at 98-103 (1980) and 2 M. Dixon and F. Woodside, Drug Product Liaiblity \'a7 11.02[1] (1989); Hughson v. St. Francis Hospital, 459 N.Y.S.2d 814 (N.Y. App. 1984) (pregnant woman's consent to medical procedures is binding on subsequently born child); Needham v. White Laboratories, 847 F.2d 355 (7th Cir. 1988), (adequate warning provided to pregnant women sufficient to preclude "failure to warn" claim by later born child).  In the medical malpractice context, the informed consent decisions are premised on respect for personal autonomy and the notion that competent adults should be permitted to make reasoned risk assessments for themselves and minor children (and fetuses).  This approach is, of course, consistent with that taken by Congress in Title VII, see, Point I, supra, and effectively disposes of Judge Posner's concern about the problem of irreducible risks.  See Pet. App. at 66a and 69a.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*47]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 C.  The Court Below And Other Courts Of Appeals Have Failed To Implement Title VII As Congress Intended.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In its decision to permit a "business necessity" defense, the court below purported to follow two decisions rendered by other circuits. n69 Both of those cases, however, represent significant departures from the statutory scheme, as it has been consistently interpreted by this Court. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n69 Wright v. Olin Corp. 697 F.2d 1172 and Hayes v. Shelby Mem. Hosp., 726 F.2d 1543.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In Wright v. Olin Corp., the court acknowledged that a sex-based policy of exclusion could not satisfy the BFOQ standard, 697 F.2d at 1185-86, n.21, and then rejected that analysis specifically to permit a defense, predictably distorting Title VII in the process.  While it is true, as that court notes, that a Title VII plaintiff may advance different theories, it is not correspondingly true that a defendant may proffer any defense regardless of the nature of the prima facie case.  Rather, the defense, to be availing, must specifically match the gravamen of the claim.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Claims and defenses in Title VII cases can be generally grouped in three separate tiers.  At one \b \i0 \ul0 [*48]\b0 \i0 \ul0   level is the individual disparate treatment case, in which intentional discrimination is inferred from differential treatment.  Articulation of a non-discriminatory reason provides a defense to the prima facie case, which can then be rebutted by proof that the proferred explanation is a pretext for discrimination. n70 Intent is irrelevant in disparate impact cases, which focus on the effects of discrimination, as shown by a statistically significant effect of a neutral policy on a protected group.  The employer must show that "the challenged practice serves, in a significant way, the legitimate employment goals of the employer." n71 Finally, overt facial discrimination can only be justified by the most rigorous standard, BFOQ, and is otherwise flatly prohibited.  See p.45 n. 60, supra. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n70 E.g., Texas Dep't of Community Affairs v. Burdine, 450 U.S. 248 (1981). The inapplicability of this analysis to cases involving overt discrimination is conceded in Wright and Hayes. Cf. Trans World Airlines v. Thurston, 469 U.S. 111 (1985).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n71 Wards Cove Packing Co. v. Antonio, 490 U.S.  , 109 S.Ct. 2115 (1989) ("business necessity" defense).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A sex \b \i0 \ul0 [*49]\b0 \i0 \ul0   or pregnancy-based policy cannot be deemed "neutral." Title VII has been amended specifically to preclude that construction.  See Point IIA, supra. Nevertheless, the Wright court applied the lower level business necessity defense, which was crafted for cases not involving intentional or overt discrimination.  Congress clearly stated that where overt or intentional discrimination is involved, the challenged practice can be justified only as a BFOQ.  The approach adopted by the Fourth Circuit is thus unauthorized, illogical and, as a matter of law, must be rejected. n72 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n72 See also Becker, supra note 21 at 1251, 1260-63.  This distinction between overt discrimination and discrimination resulting from neutral practices is not mere "semantic quibbling," Wright, 697 F.2d at 1186, but has substantial significance.  Under Title VII, the employer has always borne the burden of proof to justify a demonstrably discriminatory policy.  E.g., Dothard v. Rawlinson, 433 U.S. 321. That rule has been altered in cases involving disparate impact, but not in those involving intentional discrimination.  Compare Wards Cove Packing Co. v. Atonio, 490 U.S.  , 109 S.Ct 2115 with Price-Waterhouse v. Hopkins, U.S.  , 109 S.Ct. 1755 (mixed motive).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*50]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Hayes court embraced a different, but related, error in its desire to permit a defense.  Ignoring the male and female employee/parents who are the intended beneficiaries of Title VII, that court decided that a policy that protected their offspring "neutrally," i.e. provided the same level of protection, was a "neutral policy," justifiable by business necessity.  But, once again, Title VII unequivocally rejects any contention that an overt pregnancy or sex-based policy can be "neutral," n73 regardless of its effect on offspring.  By definition, it is not neutral with respect to workers, who may nor may not become parents, and it is their rights Title VII protects. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n73 It was precisely this fiction the PDA was intended to eliminate.  See Newport News Shipbuilding & Dry Dock Co. v. EEOC, 462 U.S. 669. (1983).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Supreme Court has unequivocally rejected the notion that sex-based classifications can somehow be justified because of arguably "neutral" effects:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 . . .the Department argues that the absence of a discriminatory effect on women as a class justifies an employment practice which, on its face, discriminated against individual employees because of their \b \i0 \ul0 [*51]\b0 \i0 \ul0   sex.  But even if the Department's actuarial evidence is sufficient to prevent plaintiffs from establishing a prima facie case on the theory that the effect of the practice on women as a class was discriminatory, that evidence does not defeat the claim that the practice, on its face, discriminated against every individual woman employed by the Department.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  Manhart, 435 U.S. at 716. This Court has also held that it is no defense to intermediate acts of discrimination that the final result of an employment process, or "bottom line," is non-discriminatory.  Connecticut v. Teal, 457 U.S. 440 (1982). Thus, even if the "bottom line" - the effect on offspring - were the same for women and men, it remains true that women are subjected to discriminatory treatment because Johnson Controls' policy and others like it impose on them terms and conditions of employment which are not applied to men.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In sum, the disparate treatment "business necessity" analysis applied in Wright, Hayes and the court below is inappropriate here.  Johnson Controls' policy can be justified only as a BFOQ.  However, because women can perform the jobs at issue, this defense is unavailing as \b \i0 \ul0 [*52]\b0 \i0 \ul0   a matter of law.  A contrary result would conflict with the plain language of Title VII and the central goals underlying the legislation.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 CONCLUSION
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Wherefore, amici urge the Court to reverse the decision of the Seventh Circuit and remand with instructions to enter judgment for petitioners.
