\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Statements of Interest of Organizational Amici Curiae
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The AMERICAN CIVIL LIBERTIES UNION (ACLU) is a nationwide, non-partisan organization of over 250,000 members.  The Women's Rights Project of the ACLU Foundation was established to work toward the elimination of the pervasive problem of gender-based discrimination.  It has participated in the litigation of many cases challenging sex discrimination in employment and discrimination against women of childbearing capacity.  The American Civil Liberties Union of Wisconsin \b \i0 \ul0 [*53]\b0 \i0 \ul0   is the Wisconsin state affiliate of the ACLU.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The AMALGAMATED CLOTHING AND TEXTILE WORKERS UNION (ACTWU) is an international trade union, with 260,000 members in the apparel, textile and related industries.  It has many members -- both women and men -- exposed to lead and other reproductive chemical hazards in a wide variety of industries.  Many of these workers will be directly affected by the principles established in this case.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The AMERICAN ASSOCIATION OF UNIVERSITY WOMEN (AAUW), a national organization of over 140,000 college-educated women and men, is strongly committed to promoting and achieving legal, social, educational and economic equity for women.  For more than a century AAUW has worked toward those goals by responsible participation in public policy issues at local, state, national and international levels.  AAUW supports constitutional protection for the rights of all individuals and opposes all forms of discrimination.  Therefore, AAUW has a strong interest in the outcome of this case.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The AMERICAN FEDERATION OF STATE, COUNTY AND MUNICIPAL EMPLOYEES, AFL-CIO, (AFSCME), which represents approximately one million public employees, is the nation's largest public employee \b \i0 \ul0 [*54]\b0 \i0 \ul0   labor union.  AFSCME represents many men and women in the health care and sanitation industries whose jobs continuously expose them to hazardous toxic substances and chemicals.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The AMERICAN FRIENDS SERVICE COMMITTEE has since 1917 been active in works of humanitarian relief and service, reconciliation among nations and peoples, and programs to overcome discrimination and oppression.  The AFSC carries out its work as a service agency of the Society of Friends in America.  The AFSC has a vital interest in this litigation because of our belief in the infinite worth of each human being and the equality of all human beings in the sight of God.  This belief has led the AFSC to commit a significant portion of its resources to work which seeks to root out the causes of violence in society which lie in poverty and imbalance of wealth, in exclusion, and denial of rights.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 AFSC works in this country and in other parts of the world in support of the efforts of women to have access to jobs that provide adequate income in workplaces that are free of hazards.  We have worked for the past decade, in parts of Appalachia in support of women challenging exclusion from jobs in coal mining and road \b \i0 \ul0 [*55]\b0 \i0 \ul0   construction, the only well-paid jobs available to people without college degrees.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In addition AFSC has worked along the Mexico - U.S. border for more than twenty years in programs dealing with health, human rights and economic development.  In the 1970s we became concerned about the impact of maquiladoras, the foreign-owned assembly plants located in Mexico along the border between the two countries.  We have seen vividly the impact on the health and safety of the young women who work at extremely low wages - $ 4 a day or less - in plants which give little attention to health and safety considerations.  One of these plants is owned by Johnson Controls in Reynosa, Mexico, making automation controls, including day long work with lead solder.  Our staff report that the company does not provide warnings in Spanish of the danger of lead exposure to fetuses, does not test workers' blood and actively recruits young women workers.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Thus for us, the present case deals with issues of exclusion and of safety in which we have a longstanding and profound interest.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The ASIAN IMMIGRANT WOMEN ADVOCATES (AIWA) educates and organizes Asian immigrant women employed as seamstresses, hotel maids,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*56]\b0 \i0 \ul0   waitresses, nursing aides, and electronic assemblers.  Many of these immigrant women suffer from extremely poor working conditions and occupational hazards.  For instance, the electronics industry has a high rate of occupation related illnesses compared to other businesses.  Environmental pollution is also a problem in neighborhoods near electronic plants, where toxics have been discovered in the water and residents have reported a higher incidence of birth defects and miscarriages.  Seamstresses develop respiratory diseases, eye strain, and muscle pains from inhaling dust, threads and fabric dyes.  Therefore, AIWA has a strong interest in the outcome of this case affecting the working conditions and rights of working women.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The BOSTON WOMEN'S HEALTH BOOK COLLECTIVE is a non-profit organization devoted to education about women and health.  Its many projects and services include a women's Health Information Center, which is open to the public, and the extensive distribution of materials to the public about women and health.  In addition, the Collective has authored a major publication concerning women and health, Our Bodies, Our Selves, which has been translated into thirteen foreign \b \i0 \ul0 [*57]\b0 \i0 \ul0   languages.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The CENTER FOR CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS (CCR) was born of the civil rights movement and the struggle of Black people in the United States for true equality.  CCR attorneys have been active in cases involving employment discrimination, voting rights, jury composition, and fair housing.  Through litigation and public education, CCR has worked to protect and make meaningful the constitutional rights of women, Blacks, Puerto Ricans, Native Americans and Chicanos.  CCR attorneys served as counsel of record for the amici supporting the right of unwed mothers to employment in the public school system in Andrews v. Drew Municipal Separate School District, 507 F.2d 611 (5th Cir. 1975), cert. dismissed as improvidently granted, 425 U.S. 559 (1976).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The CENTRAL NEW YORK COUNCIL ON OCCUPATIONAL SAFETY AND HEALTH is a not-for-profit organization dedicated to workers' health and safety rights.  Its members include 40 area union locals, individual organized and unorganized workers, concerned health providers, attorneys, educators, and others.  It believes the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals' decision in this case undermines the OSHA lead standard and the health \b \i0 \ul0 [*58]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of all workers.  Furthermore, the decision simultaneously restricts women's employment opportunities and leaves men exposed to hazardous work conditions.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The COAL EMPLOYMENT PROJECT is a national membership organization of women coal miners and their supporters.  Since its founding in 1977, CEP has supported women miners in efforts to open up mining jobs for women, eliminate discrimination and harassment, and improve health and safety conditions for all miners.  The outcome of this case is of vital importance to our membership.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The COALITION OF LABOR UNION WOMEN is America's only national organization for union women, with 75 chapters across the county and over 20,000 members representing 60 unions.  CLUW is dedicated to ending job discrimination against women and minorities, defending the right of each woman to make reproductive decisions in private, and achieving safe and healthy working conditions for all workers.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The COMMITTEE FOR RESPONSIBLE GENETICS is a group of approximately 600 scientists and others concerned with social and ethical implications of biotechnology, including reproductive technology, which promotes the broadest possible public participation in development \b \i0 \ul0 [*59]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of relevant decisions.  The Committee for Responsible Genetics opposes exclusionary employment practices because they violate workers' civil rights and fail to ensure the reproductive health of all employees in the workplace.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The COMMUNICATIONS WORKERS OF AMERICA (CWA) is an international trade union, representing 650,000 workers in information industries.  It has many members -- both men and women -- who are exposed to toxic chemicals in their work and therefore are directly affected by the principles established in this case.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The CONNECTICUT WOMEN'S EDUCATION AND LEGAL FUND, INC. was incorporated in 1973 as a non-profit public interest law firm advocating for women's legal rights.  We have over 500 members and serve thousands of people in New England each year through our litigation, community education, research and information and referral programs.  We choose to join this case as an amicus curiae because we have worked with thousands of women workers who have suffered serious economic and personal losses as a result of workplace discrimination.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The EMPLOYMENT LAW CENTER, a project of the Legal Aid Society of San Francisco, is a private non-profit public interest law firm \b \i0 \ul0 [*60]\b0 \i0 \ul0   which specializes in employment discrimination.  Founded in 1916 to represent individuals unable to afford legal counsel, the Center is dedicated to the eradication of all forms of employment discrimination including sex discrimination.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Employment Law Center is counsel for Queen E. Foster in Johnson Controls, Inc. v. California (Fair Employment and Housing Commission and Queen Elizabeth Foster), which was recently decided in the California Court of Appeal and was denied review by the California Supreme Court.  Ms. Foster applied for a position with Johnson Controls at their Fullerton, California plant and was denied employment because she refused to provide medical evidence documenting her inability to conceive children.  In an unanimous opinion, the Court of Appeal ruled in Ms. Foster's favor and held that Johnson Controls "fetal protection" policy violated California's prohibition against discrimination on the basis of sex.  Prior to representing Ms. Foster, the Employment Law Center participated as an amicus curiae in Wright v. Olin Corp., 697 F.2d 1172 (4th Cir. 1982).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In the area of sex discrimination, the Employment Law Center has also filed amicus curiae \b \i0 \ul0 [*61]\b0 \i0 \ul0   briefs in the United States Supreme Court including California Federal Savings & Loan Association v. Guerra; Hopkins v. Price Waterhouse; Meritor Savings Bank, FSB v. Vinson; Rotary International; and Wygant v. Jackson Board of Education.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The INTERNATIONAL CHEMICAL WORKERS UNION, AFL - CIO is a national labor organization headquartered in Akron, Ohio.  It has over 300 affiliated local unions in over 500 bargaining units, representing about 40,000 hourly workers in the U.S. chemical industry.  Many of its members are occupationally exposed to lead, as well as other chemicals.  The Union is concerned that a company may discriminate in work assignments rather than reducing exposure levels to make the workplace safe for workers of both sexes.  This is a particularly critical concern with exposure to material such as lead, which has demonstrable reproductive effects for men as well as women.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The MAINE LABOR GROUP ON HEALTH is a statewide, non-profit organization dedicated to protecting the health and safety of Maine working people and their families.  It provides worker educational programs and serves as workers' advocates within the health care system and in the public policy arena.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*62]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The MASSACHUSETTS CHAPTER OF THE NATIONAL LAWYERS GUILD, was founded in 1937, in part to counter the exclusionary policies of the American Bar Association which at the time did not admit Black attorneys to membership, the NATIONAL LAWYERS GUILD and its MASSACHUSETTS CHAPTER have a long history of opposing exclusionary employment policies.  The MASSACHUSETTS CHAPTER, with over 325 members, has a working committee on reproductive rights which is involved in legal and educational efforts to protect reproductive rights, including the rights of all workers to be free from reproductive hazards in the workplace.  The organization is opposed to "fetal protection" policies unilaterally adopted by employers which exclude women of child-bearing capacity from jobs and employment benefits and fail to protect the health and safety of all workers - male and female.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The MASSACHUSETTS COALITION FOR OCCUPATIONAL SAFETY AND HEALTH (MassCOSH) is a coalition of 85 labor organizations, representing over 150,000 workers and 150 occupational health professionals in Massachusetts.  MassCOSH is dedicated to improving health and safety conditions in the workplace through technical assistance, training, and \b \i0 \ul0 [*63]\b0 \i0 \ul0   education and political action.  MassCOSH, which has a reproductive hazards project and regularly conducts workshops with member locals regarding reproductive hazards in the workplace, believes that all workers are entitled to a safe workplace.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The MEXICAN AMERICAN LEGAL DEFENSE AND EDUCATIONAL FUND (MALDEF), established in 1967, is a national civil rights organization headquartered in Los Angeles.  Its principal objective is to assure, through litigation and education, the civil rights of Hispanics living in the United States.  Given the increased representation of Latinas in our nation's workforce, many of MALDEF's efforts are directed at eliminating discriminatory barriers to equal employment opportunities.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL ABORTION RIGHTS ACTION LEAGUE (NARAL) has over 400,000 members in 41 state affiliates and the national organization.  NARAL is dedicated to guaranteeing women the full range of reproductive choices, including the right to bear children without economic sanctions, which is critical to women's autonomy and equality.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 9 TO 5, NATIONAL ASSOCIATION OF WORKING WOMEN, is a nationwide membership group dedicated to improving the status and working conditions of office \b \i0 \ul0 [*64]\b0 \i0 \ul0   workers.  For more than seventeen years, 9 to 5 has been concerned with bringing attention to the health and safety hazards faced by working women.  We strongly believe that employers should meet their legal obligations to provide safe workplaces to all workers, and are opposed to the exclusion of women as a substitute for correcting job hazards.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL BLACK WOMEN'S HEALTH PROJECT is a health, education and advocacy organization which works to improve the quality of life for African-American women.  It works to promote non-discriminatory approaches to insure that all African-American women have access to health services, including abortion, that maximize maternal health, reduce infant mortality and produce healthy babies.  Because poor African-American women are particularly vulnerable to economic coercion, the impact of exclusionary policies may be particularly severe for them.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL COUNCIL OF JEWISH WOMEN, founded in 1893, the National Council of Jewish Women (NCJW) is the oldest Jewish women's volunteer organization in America.  NCJW's 100,000 members in more than 200 sections across the United States keep the organization's promise to dedicate themselves, in \b \i0 \ul0 [*65]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the spirit of Judaism, to advancing human welfare and the democratic way of life through a combination of social action, education and community service.  Based on NCJW's National Resolutions that include working for "employment policies which safeguard the dignity, rights, benefits, health and safety of all workers," it joins this brief.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL LAWYERS GUILD is a national organization representing over 8,000 lawyers, legal workers, law students and jailhouse lawyers in over 200 chapters throughout the United States.  Since its founding 1937, the Guild has provided legal support to virtually every struggle in this country for economic, social and political justice.  The Guild is firmly committed and works actively to protect the rights of all people, and specifically the right of women to equal access to employment.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL ORGANIZATION FOR WOMEN (NOW) is a national membership organization of approximately 150,000 women and men in about 700 chapters throughout the country.  It is a leading advocate of women's equality in all areas of life.  One of its priorities is assuring the right to full employment opportunity without a sacrifice of health or reproductive rights.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*66]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL UNION OF HOSPITAL AND HEALTH CARE EMPLOYEES, AFSCME, AFL - CIO (NUHHCE), is a labor organization representing approximately 38,000 professional and non-professional hospital and health care workers.  Many of its members - male and female - are regularly exposed to numerous toxic substances and hazardous chemicals in their workplace and would be directly affected by the principles established in this case.  Because of its historic and activist opposition to discrimination of all kinds and its concern for the health of all workers and the public, NUHHCE has a strong interest in this case.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL WOMEN'S HEALTH NETWORK (NWHN) is a public interest organization whose membership, comprised of 10,000 individuals and 400 organizations representing 500,000 women, seeks to give women a voice in the health care system in the United States.  NWHN supports women's right to have complete control over their bodies, particularly the right to decide when, where and how to give birth, and opposes policies which condition employment on the loss of fertility.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL WOMEN'S POLITICAL CAUCUS (NWPC) is a nationwide membership organization dedicated to the election and appointment \b \i0 \ul0 [*67]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of more women to political office.  NWPC also works to ensure equality for women in all aspects of life.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NEW YORK COUNCIL ON OCCUPATIONAL SAFETY AND HEALTH (NYCOSH) is a non-profit membership organization dedicated to the right of all workers to safe and healthy working conditions.  Its membership includes over 160 union locals and regional councils, as well as individual workers, medical and legal professionals and community activists, all working together to eliminate workplace hazards.  NYCOSH, which has a reproductive hazards committee, believes that exclusionary policies are not the appropriate solution to reproductive hazards in the workplace.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NORTH CAROLINA OCCUPATIONAL SAFETY AND HEALTH PROJECT (NCOSH) is a private, non-profit membership organization working to improve occupational safety and health conditions for all North Carolinians.  Approximately 70 local unions representing 27,000 workers and 400 health and legal professionals concerned about occupational health are NCOSH members.  NCOSH believes that exclusionary employment practices and policies are inappropriate and illegal solutions to the problem of dangerous occupational exposures.  Exclusionary policies \b \i0 \ul0 [*68]\b0 \i0 \ul0   violate the rights of women to pursue equal employment and the rights of all workers to a safe workplace.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 NORTHWEST WOMEN'S LAW CENTER is a private, non-profit organization in Seattle, Washington, that works to advance the legal rights of women by means of litigation, legislation, education, and providing information and referrals.  Protecting women's freedom of reproductive choice is one of the Law Center's priority issue areas.  The Law Center has participated in several cases involving reproductive rights before the U.S. Supreme Court and other courts.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The OCCUPATIONAL SAFETY AND HEALTH LAW CENTER (OSHLC) is a public interest law firm which represents individuals, families, organizations, and unions in health and safety matters.  The OSHLC has an on-going concern with regard to reproductive rights and the protection of both men and women on the job from any risk to those rights.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The OIL, CHEMICAL AND ATOMIC WORKERS INTERNATIONAL UNION (OCAW) has 100,000 members, a substantial number of whom are employed in industries and are potentially affected by exclusionary employment policies similar to the one at issue in this case.  The OCAW opposes exclusionary policies which single \b \i0 \ul0 [*69]\b0 \i0 \ul0   out members of one sex, and it actively seeks to develop and encourage the use of policies which will protect the health of all workers.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The PHILADELPHIA AREA PROJECT ON OCCUPATIONAL SAFETY AND HEALTH (PHILAPOSH) is a private, non-profit corporation which seeks to promote the health and safety of employees in Eastern Pennsylvania, Southern New Jersey, and the State of Delaware.  PHILAPOSH has approximately 175 affiliated local unions with a combined individual membership of over 200,000.  PHILAPOSH has regularly participated in litigation which raises important health and safety issues, either as a party or as amicus curiae. Over the last several years, PHILAPOSH has presented a number of workshops and conferences on reproductive hazards in the workplace and issues of particular concern to women workers.  PHILAPOSH has published a pamphlet, "Getting Job Hazards Out of the Bedroom."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The PLANNED PARENTHOOD FEDERATION OF AMERICA (PPFA) is a not-for-profit corporation organized in 1922.  It is the nation's oldest and largest voluntary family planning agency.  Its 180 affiliates in forty-three states and the District of Columbia provide medical, educational and counseling services to \b \i0 \ul0 [*70]\b0 \i0 \ul0   meet the family planning needs of over two million Americans per year.  PPFA believes that the ability to regulate one's own fertility is a basic human right and is concerned that female workers not be penalized in their exercise of that right.  The organization further believes that this issue can and must be resolved in a manner that protects the health interests of all workers and their children without sacrificing the workers' rights to equal employment opportunity.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The ROCHESTER COUNCIL ON OCCUPATIONAL SAFETY AND HEALTH (ROCOSH) is a non-profit organization comprised of unions, health and legal professionals, industrial hygienists, educators, and concerned individuals who believe all working people are entitled to a safe and healthy workplace.  Our union affiliates represent about 32,000 persons.  ROCOSH is interested in this case because of its belief that working people should not have to choose between making a living or preserving their life and health.  Upholding Johnson Controls' "fetal protection policy" would pervert OSHA's mandate that employers provide a safe workplace and would threaten womens' employment opportunities.  If allowed to stand, this decision could have \b \i0 \ul0 [*71]\b0 \i0 \ul0   implications for several workplaces in the Rochester area.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The SANTA CLARA CENTER FOR OCCUPATIONAL SAFETY AND HEALTH (SC-COSH) is a group representing 170 labor unions, workers and occupational health professionals in northern California, dedicated to improving health and safety conditions in the workplace.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The SERVICE EMPLOYEES INTERNATIONAL UNION (SEIU) represents 925,000 workers in the U.S. and Canada.  Its workers work primarily in the service sector, in a broad spectrum of workplaces including hospitals, offices, and food service facilities where they are exposed to toxic substances that adversely affect reproduction and health generally.  The use of exclusionary practices, instead of a comprehensive approach to health protection, could threaten the economic status of a large number of members.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 SILICON VALLEY TOXICS COALITION based in San Jose, California, includes labor unions, environmental organizations, doctors and other public health workers, fire fighters, clergy, and neighborhood organizations.  It advocates that industry and government must protect the public health and works to prevent exposure of the public to toxic substances.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The UNITED MINE WORKERS OF AMERICA,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*72]\b0 \i0 \ul0   [INTERNATIONAL UNION (UMWA)], is a 100-year old organization which represents approximately 150,000 miners and retirees in North America.  The UMWA is committed to the complete elimination of impediments to job opportunities based on race and gender.  The UMWA believes that employers must remove and protect against work-related health hazards.  Barring women or others from jobs due to those hazards is an evasion of the employer's responsibility for workplace health and safety.  Moreover, such exclusionary policies do not promote safety because men remain exposed to the hazards.  Rather, these practices shift the risks and burdens of an unhealthy work environment to those least able to bear them.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The WESTERN NEW YORK COUNCIL ON OCCUPATIONAL SAFETY & HEALTH (WNYCOSH) is an organization comprised of 60 area union locals (representing 55,000 workers) and a number of health professionals in the Western New York area.  WNYCOSH is part of a consortium of organizations, including the Cornell-Chemical Hazards Information Program, the SUNY Buffalo Toxicology Research Center, and the Union Occupational Health Center Clinic which cooperate in providing educational and technical assistance \b \i0 \ul0 [*73]\b0 \i0 \ul0   services to workers in the region.  WNYCOSH is concerned that any judicial decision that undermines the OSHA lead standard is inappropriate since there is evidence that lead constitutes a reproductive hazard for both sexes.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 WIDER OPPORTUNITIES FOR WOMEN has worked nationally and in Washington, D.C. for twenty-five years to achieve economic independence and equality of opportunity for women and girls.  WOW has a solid track record of achieving advances for women in economic policies, employment practices and employment and training programs.  As an organization committed to improving the economic and employment status of women, WOW is deeply concerned about the protection of women's rights on the job.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The WOMEN'S ECONOMIC AGENDA PROJECT (WEAP) is a California state-wide, multi-racial, cross-class women's rights and empowerment organization.  Our work includes the fight for public policies that support low income women, because women and children are the majority of the impoverished population.  Today, both women in the paid workforce and AFDC mothers worry about adequate income for food, rent, health care and decent and affordable child care.  WEAP has a long standing policy against \b \i0 \ul0 [*74]\b0 \i0 \ul0   laws that block job and training advancement because of pregnancy, as well as other gender and race based discrimination policies.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 WOMEN EMPLOYED, based in Chicago, Illinois, has a national membership of 3,000.  It assists working women with problems of sex discrimination and health and safety issues.  Because the policy at issue in this case threatens womens' employment rights, it is of particular concern to Women Employed.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 WOMEN'S LAW PROJECT (WLP) is a nonprofit feminist law firm which seeks to advance the legal and economic status of women through litigation, public education, and individual counseling.  During the past fifteen years of its existence, WLP's activities have included work in the areas of reproductive freedom, pregnancy discrimination, and employment discrimination.  WLP is dedicated to eliminating discrimination against women based on childbearing capacity and to securing the right of women workers to equal access to safe workplaces.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 WORKSAFE FOR HEALTHY COMMUNITIES is a coalition of organizations and individuals representing labor, business, environmentalists, health professionals, community based organizations, and others in California.  Worksafe is dedicated \b \i0 \ul0 [*75]\b0 \i0 \ul0   to: (1) educating the public about the need for worker protection and the relationship between control of workplace hazards, community health and environmental protection; and (2) seeking to ensure that California establishes an effective and comprehensive workplace protection program that will serve as a model for the nation.  Worksafe opposes exlusionary employment practices because they fail to control toxic use at its source and result in discrimination against workers.  Worksafe believes that an effective workplace and environmental hazard control program must seek to reduce and control toxic use, rather than controlling worker fertility.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Statements of Interest of Individual Amici Curiae
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF VICKY BUTTICE
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I worked for five years in a high lead department of a chemical factory.  Though the work was hard, the pay (about $ 13.00/hour) and benefits were very good.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I was told, both at my job interview and during the orientation on my first day of work, that the research on the dangers of working around lead were still out and that there were no conclusions, either pro or con that could be drawn from the research.  I was therefore surprised to learn after \b \i0 \ul0 [*76]\b0 \i0 \ul0   I had worked there for a while that management had introduced a policy which prohibited all women who could conceive from working in the high lead areas.  At the time I learned about the policy I was also told that if I wanted to continue working around lead I would have to give personnel a letter from my doctor confirming that I could not have children.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 At this time I was married and had no plans to have any children.  I thought that I would be exempt from the policy because my husband had had a vasectomy.  However the plant manager told me that even though my husband had been sterilized I could still "screw around."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I was informed by a personnel representative that I could definitely keep my job in the high lead area if I would agree to being sterilized.  However I would have to have an examination by the company doctor to determine if I could have children and sign a paper stating that I would not sue the company.  I refused to sign the paper, and within a few days, I was laid off.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I eventually took a job at a fast-food restaurant at a substantial cut in pay.  It took me a long time to find work after my layoff because the economic situation in my community and the surrounding \b \i0 \ul0 [*77]\b0 \i0 \ul0   area is very bad.  There are no other companies within 20-25 miles of where I live that offer comparable salaries or benefits to those of the chemical plant.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 My layoff made things very difficult for both my husband and myself.  When I began work at the chemical plant, we had taken a mortgage to buy our house.  In addition to his full time job at the chemical plant, my husband had to take a part-time job in construction and work seven days a week.  Even with my husband working so much, we were barely making ends meet.  The loss of income from my salary also created a lot of tension between us.  During that time we seemed to argue often over money and how we were going to pay our bills.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF CYNTHIA GARZA
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1979 I began working for a battery manufacturer because that plant is the best place to work in my town in terms of its salaries and benefits.  I was hired as an order checker in the shipping department, but was transferred several times into jobs that paid more and gave me the chance to earn shift premiums, which helped a lot in paying my bills.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1985, I became pregnant a second time.  The department where I worked at that time was not a high lead area,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*78]\b0 \i0 \ul0   but when the personnel director learned that I was pregnant I was told that I couldn't stay on the job.  I wasn't given any reason, and even my doctor said that I could continue working.  The personnel director informed me that if I had wanted to keep my job then I shouldn't have gotten pregnant.  I filed a grievance through the union for discrimination, but in a meeting I and the shop steward had with the personnel director, I was told that the only way I could get my job back would be to lose the baby.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I was very upset.  Nobody was able to help.  The union was unable to do anything and my doctor refused to sign the papers for disability because he said that I could still work.  A few days after my meeting with the personnel director, I miscarried the pregnancy.  I had been approximately thirteen to fourteen weeks pregnant.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF PAT GRANT
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1976 I began working in the foundry of an automobile plant.  At that time I had one child.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The first time I learned about the policy excluding women of childbearing capacity was late in 1980, after I had already had my second child, when I was told to go to the company's medical department.  They told me that I could \b \i0 \ul0 [*79]\b0 \i0 \ul0   not continue to work in the foundry as an iron pourer because this job exposed me to a high level of lead.  I was also told that in order to keep my job I would have to be sterilized.  There were no exceptions to the policy, even though I told the medical people that I was then using birth control and had no plans for becoming pregnant.  I objected to the policy and, along with other women in the plant, filed a grievance with the union against the company for discrimination.  The union negotiated a slightly modified policy with the company and I remained on my job.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Between 1979 and 1983 I was laid off due to a general work slow down.  When I was called back to work I was transferred to iron pouring.  However after a few weeks I was removed again because of the policy and as a result I filed charges of discrimination and harassment with a state agency.  Because of my complaint I was harassed and threatened with discharge.  However because of my seniority I transferred to another department and have only worked in iron pouring as a temporary replacement for another worker for three months in 1985.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 After the policy was modified all the women were closely monitored for blood lead levels \b \i0 \ul0 [*80]\b0 \i0 \ul0   and if their lead level was too high they were either moved to another department where the air lead level was lower or they had to wear respirators.  Transfer to another department meant losing about $ .45 or $ .50/hour in salary.  There was also less overtime and weekend work in the low lead departments.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1984, two women were removed because they had high blood lead levels and told they could not return even when their lead level dropped to normal because the air lead level was too high.  However again, I was allowed to work their overtime, probably because I had filed the charges.  By the end of 1984 I was under a lot of stress.  I was always under pressure on my job because of harrassment from my foreman.  The company had modified its policy somewhat, and other women were allowed to return to high lead areas, but I was not, except as a relief worker.  Even after several years, I don't feel that my job in the melting department is secure, because could move me at any time.  I also think the policy is psychologically degrading because keeping my job doesn't really depend on whether I'm good at my work or have seniority, but hangs only on whether I can have children.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I liked \b \i0 \ul0 [*81]\b0 \i0 \ul0   my job as an iron pourer very much and don't want to work at anything else.  However I have not been able to return to this job on a steady basis.  The company has no openings in the skilled trades and they are not adding new jobs.  There are also no other companies in this area of the state that pay as high a salary and offer such good benefits as the automobile plant.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF ALVA LEWIS
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I have been employed in an automobile plant for twenty-five years, and work in the skilled trades as a millwright.  I believe that the plant has always had a policy of testing the blood/lead levels of people who worked in the high lead areas.  However, I don't believe this policy was routinely enforced.  For example, my brother worked in the foundry and the melting area melting ore for about twenty-six years, but as far as I know he had only one blood test.  In 1978 or 1979, he was tested and had a very high blood/lead level.  In 1980 or 1981 he collapsed on the job melting ore (iron) in the melting area.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 My brother was forty-four years old when he had the heart attack, and due to the events surrounding his heart attack, I strongly believe his heart attack may very well have \b \i0 \ul0 [*82]\b0 \i0 \ul0   been caused by the many years he spent working in the high lead melting area and nearby areas.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 When the company enforced its policy with respect to women working in the high lead areas, I was a union Committeeman At Large and at first I thought it was a good idea.  However I, and the other representatives, also recognized that the jobs in these areas paid higher wages and often offered more overtime than jobs in other departments in the plant.  After debate and consultation the union decided to support the women because we thought that the policy discriminated against women who wanted and probably needed to work in the high paying jobs to support their families.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The foundry is a very hot and dirty area of the plant and after having fabricated, installed and repaired industrial ventilation systems at this plant for the past twenty-five years, and after having had training in industrial ventilation engineering I am aware that many measures can be taken to improve this workplace.  However we have two major problems with achieving this goal.  One is after management has spent thousands and even millions to install a system, they assume the systems will last forever and ignore the need \b \i0 \ul0 [*83]\b0 \i0 \ul0   to maintain them.  They also allow amateurs who have great authority and no expertise to modify the systems to suit a particular temporary need which soon results in decreasing the efficiency of the system and in some cases nearly destroying it.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF JEANNE PATTERSON
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I began work at the electronics company in 1979.  At that time I was married, but we did not have any children.  I was a specialist in etching and enjoyed the work very much.  It required dexterity and I found it challenging.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 When I was hired I wasn't told about any personnel policy regarding pregnant workers, or about hazards in the workplace.  But when I became pregnant with my first child, my supervisor told me that I had to have my doctor sign a form authorizing my working with certain chemicals.  Before signing the form my doctor asked me whether I wanted to keep my job.  He was the one who told me that if the form was not signed, I would not have a job.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I worked throughout my first pregnancy.  But after my maternity leave, I was told that there was no job available for me and that I would be called in when something opened up.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I was finally called back to work and in a few weeks went \b \i0 \ul0 [*84]\b0 \i0 \ul0   on graveyard shift.  Later I became pregnant a second time and informed my supervisor.  This time my doctor refused to authorize my working with chemicals.  I was told by personnel that it would be difficult for them to find me another job in the company because my salary was so high and because my skills were in jobs that involved exposure to chemicals.  After a couple of weeks, I was finally offered an interview for a job in another area, but it would have meant taking a 45 percent pay cut.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Financially, my layoff created difficulties.  Our rent was raised twice during this time and there were many nights that I stayed awake worrying about paying bills.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 After my maternity leave, I called the company and told them I was ready to return to work.  After about two months, I was given a job, but with a loss in seniority and a $ .75/hour reduction in pay, and a loss of my job title.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF BETTY RIGGS
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I had several jobs prior to working in a chemical plant, but the salary and benefits in those earlier jobs were not as good.  When I heard that the chemical plant was hiring women, I applied immediately.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 My son was eight years old when I began working in the plant.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*85]\b0 \i0 \ul0   At the time my marriage was going very badly and I did not want another child until our relationship improved.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 After the company introduced the policy barring fertile women from working in all areas but two, and then several months later just in the high lead areas, the women held several meetings with management.  I believe that management pushed sterilization because they made it clear in the meetings that the only form of birth control they considered safe was sterilization.  I had asked in one of our meetings whether my husband's vasectomy was adequate protection against my becoming pregnant and was told that it was not.  According to the company's representative, I could still fool around and get pregnant.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I decided to have the sterilization because I needed to keep my job.  Management had said that when possible we would be transferred to a safe lead-free department in the factory, but those jobs paid less than what I was currently earning.  Besides, I didn't think there were enough jobs available in non-lead departments for all the women, and so I thought there was also the chance that I could be laid off.  I don't think I would have been able to manage financially without \b \i0 \ul0 [*86]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the higher paying job.  By the time the policy was introduced, I knew that my husband and I were going to separate, and that I would have to support myself and my parents who were elderly and infirm and if I had lost my job I would have had to reduce the amount of my support or even discontinue it altogether.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I was 26 years old when I was sterilized and the realization of what I had done didn't hit me until two or three weeks after the operation.  Generally I'd say that I felt less a woman because of the operation.  I think that though my marriage was in bad shape, my sterilization made things even worse.  My husband was cold, distant and unfeeling about me personally.  He just cared about the money I was bringing home.  The consequences of the sterilization have even affected my second marriage.  Both my second husband and I would have very much liked to have had a child together.  In fact I tried to have the operation reversed, but was not successful.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 At the plant those of us who had been sterilized were often harassed.  In fact I think the harassment became worse after the policy was introduced and it became especially cruel after some of us were sterilized.  I overhead four \b \i0 \ul0 [*87]\b0 \i0 \ul0   men talking about my operation and they said that I "could have had the surgery done in the carpenter shop," and another supervisor told me "that anybody can screw you now." In addition men called the women "whores" and wrote signs that said for example, "save a job, shoot a woman".
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I also think the policy created some friction in the town where the factory was located.  Even twelve years after the policy and being laid-off for eight years, I still feel uncomfortable when I attend social activities where I might meet some of my former co-workers, and there are co-workers or wives of co-workers who refuse to speak to me when we meet.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Statement of Interest of Unnamed Amici Curiae
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF JANE DOE 1
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 As soon as I heard that the chemical plant was hiring women, I applied for a job.  A few years after I started working, the company introduced the policy barring women from working in certain high lead jobs.  I was not in a department where women were barred from working.  But we were led to believe that sometime in the future women might be barred from working in all other departments where there were chemicals.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 During that time I was always worried about whether \b \i0 \ul0 [*88]\b0 \i0 \ul0   my job was safe.  I still had payments on my mobile home which I wouldn't have been able to make if I lost my job.  Generally, there was no way I could plan for a future with the policy hanging over my head.  I live alone and support myself.  After the policy was introduced, the harassment against women in the plant became much worse.  Many of the men and supervisors made us feel as though we were less than an animal.  When a woman could overhear them, they referred to the sterilizations as "going to the vets."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF JANE DOE 2
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I have worked since I was sixteen years old and held a variety of jobs as a waitress,nurses aide and in a factory.  These jobs paid low wages and had limited benefits.  I heard from friends that an automobile plant was hiring women, and I was hired in the late summer of 1976.  I worked in a high lead area of the foundry.  At that time, though no one mentioned that the lead levels were particularly high or that there was any danger.  Because of the policy I had to move to another job.  It made no difference that my husband had a vasectomy.  This job paid less money than the one in the foundry and I had to work overtime to make up the difference.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*89]\b0 \i0 \ul0   However, it was a hassle having to keep track of when my overtime came up and how many hours were worked.  It was made very clear to me that the only way I could go back and work in the foundry was by getting sterilized.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I was laid off for a few months because of a general slow down in the plant, and I returned to a low lead area in the foundry.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The economic situation in this part of the state is not good.  There is only one other factory that perhaps offers comparable benefits, but the pay scale is lower.  Some smaller factories have shut down and the others are not hiring.  If I lost my job I would either have to travel at least an hour or more round trip to another city or state, or I would have to take a job as a sales clerk or waitress.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF JANE DOE 3
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I am legally separated and have three children, and receive no child support.  A few years ago, I was laid off during the slow season from my job in a paper factory, and a couple of months later when I was supposed to return to work, the company refused to hire me back because I was pregnant.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 When I was called back after the layoff, I checked with personnel to make sure about the day I was to return \b \i0 \ul0 [*90]\b0 \i0 \ul0   to work.  Later that same day, someone from the office called me and told me not to return to work because I was pregnant.  I was told that my job operating the envelope machine was dangerous to my pregnancy because I would be standing for too long.  After some time had passed, the company changed their reason and said that in operating the envelope machine I had to stretch a lot and the company believed that would be a strain on me physically.  Finally, they told me that the chemicals in the ink printed on the paper were dangerous to my baby.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The job at the paper factory which makes paper products and "novelty" items was the best I ever had.  Both the salary and the benefits were better than any I had received on my previous jobs.  Before I was laid off I had learned to operate five or six of the seven available machines, and had received a $ 1.50/hour raise.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 When I began earning more money, I took out a personal loan to help me get ahead on some of my other bills.  I was still making payments on this loan when I was not rehired, and until I paid up the loan I was very worried that I would fall behind in my loan payments.  At this point, I have used all of my unemployment insurance.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*91]\b0 \i0 \ul0   The factory also discontinued my insurance coverage when I was not rehired.  Since March of 1989, I have had no income and no insurance and am currently receiving AFDC.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF JANE DOE 4
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 After I graduated from high school I worked part-time in a restaurant while I looked for full-time employment.  I am married and have two children.  In 1988 I went to a chemical plant to fill out applications for employment.  I was told by the personnel secretary that before I could complete an application I would first have to sign a statement that either I had been sterilized or was past menopause.  Since I was unable to sign, I could not apply for a job.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In September, I was called by the union president and told that the factory had changed its policy and that I should reapply.  This time I was given an application which included a statement to the effect that I knew about the dangers of lead and if I became pregnant while working at the factory and anything was wrong with the child I would not sue the company.  Even though I disliked signing the statement, I did so because I needed the job.  But even though I signed, I never heard from them.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This particular company is \b \i0 \ul0 [*92]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the highest paying factory in the general area where I live.  It pays about three times more than any other place around here.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF JANE DOE 5
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 After I moved back to Iowa I applied for work at every factory in my area.  One of those companies was a chemical plant, which I know offers the highest hourly wage of any employer in this area.  I was not given an application at the personnel office because I was first asked to sign a form stating that I was unable to have children.  I told them that I had children and was not planning to have any more, but was told that didn't matter.  I would still have to sign and provide proof.  I think whether or not I can have or even plan to have children in the future is a private matter.  It isn't something the company should have to know before they decide whether or not to hire me.  I refused to sign.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Later in the year I was contacted by the president of the union at the factory and told that things had changed and I could now apply for work.  Although this time I was not asked to sign a separate form, the application included a statement similar to the first one.  I completed the application but did not sign the statement.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*93]\b0 \i0 \ul0   It is now over a year since I applied for a job, but the company has never contacted me.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF JOHN DOE 1
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I have worked in the automotive industry for twenty-five years, first in New York, and now in the midwest.  During most of those years I worked in the core department where I am exposed to formaldehyde and other solvents.  I am concerned about the exposure to toxic substances because of my personal situation.  Only three of my five children are alive.  The second child was stillborn.  My third child developed cancer early in life and died at age five, and the fourth pregnancy produced twins who were prematurely born.  I am convinced that my exposure to hazardous substances in the workplace was the cause of the two deaths and possibly the premature births of the twins.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A lot of men have a hard time relating their chemical exposures to their own health problems or those of their children.  Men just assume that during a pregnancy the health of the baby can only be affected by something the mother is exposed to.  I also think for economic reasons this issue is a hard one for many people to take a stand on.  The plant where I work isn't hiring any new workers,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*94]\b0 \i0 \ul0   and all of the men here have ten, fifteen or more years seniority.  Some people are afraid that if there is too much pressure put on the company to cleanup the workplace, then the plant will close down.  This is what happened in the New York plant where I worked.  I have twenty-five years with this company and if this plant was shut down, I know that there is no factory in this area where I could even earn a third of my current salary.  You might say that we're sort of caught between a rock and a hard place.  Some men prefer to ignore the health issue and just gamble that they or their children won't get sick.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF JANE DOE 6
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I quit high school in the 10th grade, but returned eleven years later and received my graduation equivalency diploma.  After I quit school, I worked for five years as a sales clerk in a variety store.  My salary was minimum wage and I received no benefits other than hospitalization.  My next job was in a textile factory, but after a while it closed.  A year later I heard that they were hiring women at a plant.  I applied for the job because it offered a much better salary ($ 4.25/hour) and better benefits than any of the jobs I had ever \b \i0 \ul0 [*95]\b0 \i0 \ul0   had before.  Even though the work was strenuous, I enjoyed it.  The money and benefits were excellent.  A few years after I started, the women were told that management had decided to prohibit all women capable of having children from working in departments where there were dangerous chemicals.  Around this time this policy was introduced, I had to have a total hysterectomy for medical reasons.  Other women at the factory were sterilized so that they could keep their jobs.  When we went back to our jobs those of us who had been sterilized, no matter what the reason, were recognized by everyone in the plant.  The men in the plant knew about the policy and they knew I was sterilized.  Some of them harassed me, making jokes and cruel comments.  For example, shortly after I returned to work, someone put a can in my locker with the message "you didn't have to have it done in the hospital, you could have had it done in the maintenance shop." Some of the men referred to me as "one of the guys." I was so upset by this harassment that my doctor put me on medication for my nerves.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Eventually those of us who had been sterilized were recognized in town.  There were times when I walked into a \b \i0 \ul0 [*96]\b0 \i0 \ul0   store where there were other customers and someone would loudly say here comes "one of them women."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF JANE DOE 7
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 After six years in low paying jobs, I was hired in the stockroom at a chemical company.  The salary and benefits were much better than those I had received before.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I worked at the company for more than a year before I became pregnant.  When my supervisor learned that I was pregnant, she told me that I would have to stop working.  Because I complained about this policy, I was eventually told that I should get a doctor's authorization to continue working.  My doctor said that there was no harm in my working because I was not directly exposed to any dangerous chemicals.  However even with my doctor's authorization, I was laid off without any explanation.  Although I collected unemployment insurance during my layoff, I had to pay for my insurance coverage with my employer.  Because my insurance was better than my husband's, we decided to continue my policy, but it was financially a burden.  During this time I looked for other work but found only occasional jobs, through a temp agency.  I was never able to get my old job back after my baby was born, even though \b \i0 \ul0 [*97]\b0 \i0 \ul0   I tried.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 These last six months have been hard for us.  We are fortunate that my husband's parents can help us financially from time to time because we cannot make ends meet every month.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF JOHN DOE 2
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I have worked in an automobile plant for several years, and for most of that time I worked in the foundry.  In the early seventies, everyone working in the high lead areas was supposed to have periodic blood tests to determine lead levels.  It seems that this requirement wasn't enforced for the men.  I know I never had the test.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I was pouring iron when the company introduced its policy requiring all women who worked in high lead areas and whose blood tests showed high lead to transfer to low or lead free areas or to be sterilized if they were still of childbearing age.  I supported those women who objected to the policy.  I thought that the women I worked with were as capable at their jobs as any man, and I don't think it was right that they were being discriminated against.  My impression is that a lot of men felt the same way.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF JANE DOE 8
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1973, I began working in the foundry of an automobile plant.  At the time, I had one small child and when my husband \b \i0 \ul0 [*98]\b0 \i0 \ul0   and I separated I needed to find a job with a good salary and benefits.  The plant was the only place in the area that offered both and I was hired into the foundry.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1973 no one was concerned about exposure to lead.  However a few years later, after I had been transferred out of the foundry and to a department where there wasn't any lead, I heard that some of the women in the foundry had been sterilized so that they could keep their jobs.  When I was sent back to the foundry, I had to have a blood lead test every three months, and at almost every test the nurse suggested that I have a tubal ligation.  I thought the surgery wasn't necessary because my second husband had a vasectomy.  But I was told that it didn't matter whether or not my husband was sterilized.  My blood lead levels remained normal so I never had to leave the foundry.  I stayed in there for a few years until I had enough seniority to transfer to another department.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The job situation where I live is not good.  If I lost my job I would never find anything comparable to what I now have.  A woman who is in her late thirties as I am would probably only be able to get a job as a sales clerk in the shopping mall or \b \i0 \ul0 [*99]\b0 \i0 \ul0   as a waitress in a fast-food restaurant.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF INTEREST OF JANE DOE 9
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 My first industrial job was in a garment factory doing piece work.  I left there because the wages and benefits were bad and I found another industrial job in a chemical plant.  After five years I was laid off, and it took me eighteen months to find another full-time job.  But the chemical company I worked for is the largest industry in my area and pays the best wages, and when I learned that they were hiring new people, I returned there as soon as I could.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I worked in the mixed cast area, mixing rocket propellant.  I continued in this department until I became pregnant.  I think this plant discriminates against pregnant women.  I know of women who were pregnant while working at the plant and the company seems to punish us for being pregnant.  One woman who just had a baby was due for promotion and was by-passed.  They told her it was because she had been pregnant.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I am now pregnant and am especially worried that when I return from maternity leave, I won't have my old job back.  I know that they hired someone else for my position one week after I was transferred to the janitor pool.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I am the major \b \i0 \ul0 [*100]\b0 \i0 \ul0   supporter of my family.  My husband is presently laid off from his job.  My family depends on my salary and benefits, and it would be disastrous for us if I lost my job before my husband is called back to work.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENT OF JANE DOE 10
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I started working in the foundry of an automobile plant in 1972.  At that time I was married and had two small children.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 After I had worked there for about a year, management introduced a policy requiring all women working in high lead areas to have blood lead level tests every three months.  My blood lead level was always low.  However the general foreman in the department wanted to get rid of all the women.  Those of us who were not sterilized had to wear respirators.  I found the respirators very uncomfortable.  It's already hot in the foundry and the respirator just makes you hotter.  In addition, I couldn't find one that fit me right.  The general foreman kept after the women to get sterilized and finally I just decided to have the operation.  Looking back, I regret that I did it.  I come from a big family and I always wanted more children.  At the time I wasn't planning on getting married again and I really needed my job to support the children \b \i0 \ul0 [*101]\b0 \i0 \ul0   I already had.  But as things happened, I did remarry and both my husband and I wanted a child.
\par 
